posts.com:
1. Confidence, when you dont have it, life is shit. When you start building it with (true) self validation, it'll make everything better. And by true self validation, I simply mean take credit for what you actually like about yourself.

2. Build on the "what you like about yourself" and understand what type/kind of friends and groups you'd like to be a part of. You can find friends everywhere. You surely can make friends with a group of rough sleepers in the suburbs! The point is, you probably dont want that, so pick what you like.

3. Get out and go do what the people you like, usually do!
Once in you're in groups, it's usually just a matter of time before you take part and engage with more people and eventually be part of a friendship.

4. Adjust the points 2 and 3 according to your situation, and keep the confidence up all the time regardless. I dont think you have a problem with too much confidence since you deem yourseld potentially unlikeable at this point so just focus on adjusting 2 & 3 according to your life and what you can/can't do.

5. Seek therapy, if you haven't already, and if you can, seek therapy, and that'll give you measurable goals and hitting them constantly helps your confidence and it's just a domino effect after that.

Beside this,
>self validation
I understand and in part I agree with what you say, but self validation is not meaningless. It is imperative for being confident in what you do (whatever you do) and letting your brain/body work properly with no confusion.
If you are confident, relaxed and maybe proud in doing something, you WILL do that better, simply (and not only) because your brain will focus almost entirely on that, without spent time/energy focusing on other's validation.

>egoist or narcissist
You could see altruism as a 'perfect form' of egoism, if you want. The most altruistic person in the world would get more pleasure than anyone else in doing some good, so he/she would seek to get the most pleasure he/she could, like any other living being.
seeking pleasure = egoism
This is a theory (and a witty paradox, in my opinion), but pseudo-phylosophical/anthropological/logical pindaric flights do not help anybody in living better.
What do you do?
Do you like what you do?
Be honest with yourself and do not judge relative concepts without having jumped yourself in.
Do what you believe in and try to be proud of what you do. You are giving the world something that nobody else could ever give, bad or good.
Try to understand if you are in peace with yourself when you stop doing things and you are alone (before sleep, maybe). Stop a minute, ask yourself, and answer.
And don't fucking care of everything else.

>>890781901
Our eyes are filled with a jelly-like substance called vitreous that liquefies, aggregates,and generally degenerates as we age. Floaters are just bits of it that have clumped up and now float around inside your eyeball. Overwhelmingly, they are just annoying. However, large increases in floaters in a short period of time can be a sign of a more serious condition and should be checked out by an eye doc, especially if they are accompanied by flashing lights or the appearance of a curtain or veil over your vision. If you are experiencing that you are at high risk of going blind in that eye if not treated immediately. However the progression from floaters to this condition (retinal detachment) is extremely rare, like less than 0.1% or something.

>How long until we'll have cybernetic eyes? Smartphone camera tech has been advancing rapidly the past 10 years.
I don't have a good answer for this, I don't really follow this topic much at all. I think currently we have tech that can use cameras to transmit extremely rudimentary signals to nerves, but it's barely a step above being blind. My guess is cybernetic eyes that can function on a comparable level to biologic eyes is far, far away. Not in our lifetimes far away. But tech progresses exponentially, so who knows.

>Is LASIK eye treatments really that bad? It has been in the news lately, being on FDAs radar lately
I personally am not a fan of them. At the end of the day, glasses or contacts are not a hassle for me, and refractive surgeries are really just cosmetic surgeries, you are getting surgery and risking complications in a perfectly healthy and functioning organ. Nearsightedness and farsightedness is not a disease, it's generally a consequence of the length of your eye and the shape of your cornea, nothing unhealthy that needs surgery to fix. You're risking issues with glare, still needing glasses or contacts after, and in the case of nearsighted people, pushing forward the age at which you will start to need glasses for reading. On that note, every person will eventually need glasses/contacts at near as they age, refractive surgery cannot fix that without fucking up your distance vision in the process.

>What can I do to slow down age related eye sight deterioration?
I can't answer this without knowing what type of deterioration you are talking about. The biggest thing you can do for the health of your eyes is to keep your body healthy. Don't get diabetes, don't have uncontrolled hypertension, and don't smoke. These things can all fuck up your eyes too. Specifically for your eyes, try to limit UV exposure.

>>890782872
Nearsightedness is not a deterioration of your eyesight in a biological sense, it's an optical consequence largely based on the length of your eyeballs. Nearsighted people have eyes that are too long to focus light appropriately on the retina, thus causing vision blur. Nearsightedness tends to progress from childhood to our late teens or twenties as our eyeballs grow. It generally stabilizes, but can continue to change with age, either progressing further or regressing to a lesser required prescription, this is not abnormal. There are some medical conditions that can affect this but I assume for you this is not relevant.
Astigmatism is a consequence of the curvature of your cornea. Instead of the curvature being the same in all 360 degrees, it is steeper in one direction, causing vision blur or distortion/shadowing in more severe cases. Needing correction for astigmatism is not at all a scam. If an astigmatic correction improves your clarity of vision, then it's because that's how your cornea is shaped. Giving an astigmatic correction to a person without any astigmatism would only blur their vision, a pretty poor way to make more money. And just like nearsightedness, the shape of our corneas can change with age, though generally not drastically. If you no longer require astigmatic correction my guess would be you never had more than -1.00 or -2.00 diopters of cyl tops (astigmatic correction) in your glasses/contacts.

>>890785099
Blue light in general is theorized to be worse because of its shorter wavelength leading it to have higher energy than other longer wavelengths of light. But in my opinion it's largely a scam. The blue light from screens is no different than the blue light from the sun, and studies show you absorb far, far, more blue light from natural sunlight than any screen on a day to day basis. No studies that I am aware of have shown a link between electronic device use (blue light) and the development of eye disease like macular degeneration and blindness, nor does the research support the idea that it causes 'digital eyestrain.' In my opinion, all the push for blue light filters and all that shit is a scam. The only verifiable claim about blue light is that it can alter your circadian rhythm and affect your sleep quality. So if you really care a bunch about that you can just turn on night mode or whatever that's on like every iPhone nowadays instead of wasting your money on blue light filters.

jaundice
blood in the digestive tract
high blood pressure
confusion
swelling in lower extremities
fluid accumulating in the abdomen (ascites)

Liver failure due to alcoholism is extremely painful, as the body shuts down slowly, and the complications from alcohol liver disease take over.
